definition.value: A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid bearing an oxo substituent at position 4 on the cyclohexenyl ring.
A retinoid that consists of all-trans-retinoic acid bearing an hydroxy substituent at position 18.
A retinoid obtained by epoxidation across the 5,6-double bond of retinoic acid.

A hexitol derivative that is D-mannitol in which the hydroxy group at position 1 is replaced by the alpha-amino group of L-glutamine. It is produced in crown gall tumours induced in a wide range of dicotyledenous plants by Agrobacterium tumefaciens.
A phenethylamine alkaloid that is tyramine in which one of the amino hydrogens has been replaced by a 3,4-dihydroxybenzyl group.
A phenethylamine alkaloid that is norbelladine in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 4' has been replaced by a methyl group.
A member of the class of morpholines that is morpholine substituted with a phenyl group at position 2 and a methyl group at position 3.
An amphetamine that is propylbenzene substituted by a hydroxy group at position 1 and by an amino group at position 2 (the 1R,2S-stereoisomer). It is a plant alkaloid.
A member of the class of barbiturates, the structure of which is that of barbituric acid substituted at C-5 by ethyl and phenyl groups.
A barbiturate that is the sodium salt of phenobarbital (barbituric acid substituted at C-5 by ethyl and phenyl groups).
